# Data Import and Preparation

## Import

```{r}
#| label: load-data

tuesdata <- tt_load(2025, week = 4)

water_2022 <- tuesdata$water_insecurity_2022
water_2023 <- tuesdata$water_insecurity_2023
```

## Cleaning and Feature Engineering

```{r}
#| label: clean-data
#| code-fold: show

# Only non-state territories excluded — AK and HI are included
EXCLUDE_TERRITORIES <- c("Puerto Rico",
                         "United States Virgin Islands", "Guam",
                         "Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands",
                         "American Samoa")

clean_water <- function(df) {
  df |>
    mutate(
      rate   = percent_lacking_plumbing / 100,
      state  = str_extract(name, "(?<=, ).+$"),
      county = str_remove(name, ",.*$")
    ) |>
    filter(
      !is.na(rate),
      !is.na(total_pop),
      total_pop > 0,
      !state %in% EXCLUDE_TERRITORIES
    )
}

water_2023_clean <- clean_water(water_2023)
water_2022_clean <- clean_water(water_2022)
```

::: {.callout-tip}
## Why use a function rather than repeating the pipeline?
Wrapping the cleaning logic in `clean_water()` ensures that **identical
transformations** are applied to both years, eliminating any risk of
year-specific inconsistencies that would bias the 2022–2023 comparison.
Geographic exclusions defined once in `EXCLUDE_TERRITORIES` propagate
automatically to every downstream analysis. This is the *"Don't Repeat
Yourself"* (DRY) principle.
:::

## Validation

Before proceeding, we verify that `percent_lacking_plumbing / 100` and
`plumbing / total_pop` are numerically consistent.

```{r}
#| label: tbl-validation
#| tbl-cap: "Internal consistency check between the two rate derivations (2023 dataset)."

water_2023_clean |>
  mutate(check_rate = plumbing / total_pop) |>
  summarise(
    `N counties`  = n(),
    `Max |diff|`  = max(abs(rate - check_rate), na.rm = TRUE),
    `Mean |diff|` = mean(abs(rate - check_rate), na.rm = TRUE),
    `Rate > 1`    = sum(rate > 1),
    `Rate < 0`    = sum(rate < 0)
  ) |>
  kable(digits = 8)
```

The maximum absolute discrepancy is effectively zero (floating-point
rounding only), confirming that the provided percentage and the computed
rate are identical. No out-of-range values exist.

