    `Min`              = scales::percent(min(rate),    accuracy = 0.01),
    `Median`           = scales::percent(median(rate), accuracy = 0.01),
    `Mean`             = scales::percent(mean(rate),   accuracy = 0.01),
    `Max`              = scales::percent(max(rate),    accuracy = 0.01),
    `Counties > 5%`    = sum(rate > 0.05),
    `Counties > 10%`   = sum(rate > 0.10)
  ) |>
  kable()
```

::: {.callout-important}
## Mean vs. weighted national rate
The simple **mean** (`r scales::percent(mean(water_2023_clean$rate, na.rm=TRUE), accuracy=0.01)`)
weights every county equally regardless of size. The **population-weighted
rate** weights each county by its population — giving a more accurate picture
of how many *people* are affected. The two figures differ because the most
affected counties tend to be small in population.
:::

## Distribution of Deprivation Rates

```{r}
#| label: fig-distribution
#| fig-cap: "Distribution of county-level plumbing deprivation rates — all 50 states (2023). The mean (red dashed) sits above the median (grey dotted) due to right skew driven by Alaska and tribal-land counties."
#| fig-height: 4.5

nat_avg <- mean(water_2023_clean$rate, na.rm = TRUE)
nat_med <- median(water_2023_clean$rate, na.rm = TRUE)

ggplot(water_2023_clean, aes(x = rate)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(density)),
                 bins = 50, fill = "#4575b4", color = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_density(color = "#d73027", linewidth = 0.9) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = nat_avg, linetype = "dashed",
             color = "#d73027", linewidth = 0.9) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = nat_med, linetype = "dotted",
             color = "#555555", linewidth = 0.9) +
  annotate("text", x = nat_avg + 0.002, y = Inf,
           label = paste0("Mean\n", scales::percent(nat_avg, accuracy = 0.01)),
           hjust = 0, vjust = 1.4, color = "#d73027", size = 3.4,
           fontface = "bold") +
  annotate("text", x = nat_med - 0.002, y = Inf,
           label = paste0("Median\n", scales::percent(nat_med, accuracy = 0.01)),
           hjust = 1, vjust = 1.4, color = "#555555", size = 3.4,
           fontface = "bold") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 0.1),
                     breaks = seq(0, 0.6, by = 0.05)) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.15))) +
  labs(
    title    = "Distribution of Plumbing Deprivation Rates Across U.S. Counties (2023)",
    subtitle = "Strongly right-skewed: national averages conceal severe outlier communities",
    x = "Share of households lacking complete plumbing",
    y = "Density",
    caption = SOURCE_CAPTION
  )
```

@fig-distribution reveals a **strongly right-skewed distribution**. The vast
majority of counties
(`r scales::percent(mean(water_2023_clean$rate < 0.02, na.rm=TRUE), accuracy=1)`)
have rates below 2%, yet a persistent tail extends well beyond 20% and
approaches 50% in extreme Alaskan and tribal-land cases. The mean exceeds
the median by `r scales::percent(nat_avg - nat_med, accuracy = 0.01)`, a
telltale signature of distributional skew.

