As shown in @tbl-top10 and @fig-top10, the most severely affected counties
are concentrated in **Alaska and Arizona**. Alaskan communities face
prohibitive infrastructure costs due to permafrost and remoteness, while
Arizona counties — particularly those overlapping the Navajo Nation — reflect
decades of structural underinvestment in Indigenous infrastructure. The top
county exceeds `r scales::percent(max(top_counties$rate), accuracy = 0.1)`,
meaning more than half of its households lack at least one basic plumbing
facility.

## State-Level Analysis

```{r}
#| label: state-data

state_summary <- water_2023_clean |>
  group_by(state) |>
  summarise(
    n_counties    = n(),
    total_pop     = sum(total_pop, na.rm = TRUE),
    total_lacking = sum(plumbing,  na.rm = TRUE),
    weighted_rate = total_lacking / total_pop,
    mean_rate     = mean(rate,     na.rm = TRUE),
    median_rate   = median(rate,   na.rm = TRUE),
    max_rate      = max(rate,      na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) |>
  arrange(desc(weighted_rate))
```

```{r}
#| label: fig-states
#| echo: false
#| fig-cap: "Top 15 states ranked by population-weighted plumbing insecurity (2023). Dot size encodes absolute scale; colour encodes severity."
#| fig-height: 5.5

state_summary |>
  slice_head(n = 15) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = weighted_rate, y = fct_reorder(state, weighted_rate),
             size = total_lacking, color = weighted_rate)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.88) +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(weighted_rate, accuracy = 0.01)),
            hjust = -0.5, size = 3.2, color = "grey30", fontface = "bold") +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#fee090", high = "#a50026",
                       labels = scales::percent_format(), guide = "none") +
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(3, 13),
                        labels = scales::comma_format(),
                        name   = "Households\nlacking plumbing") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(),
                     expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.25))) +
  labs(
    title    = "Top 15 States by Population-Weighted Plumbing Insecurity (2023)",
    subtitle = "Weighted rate = Σ lacking / Σ population · removes bias from county size differences",
    x = "Population-weighted deprivation rate", y = NULL,
    caption = SOURCE_CAPTION
  ) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank())
```

::: {.callout-note}
## Why population-weighted rates matter
A simple average of county rates weights a county of 500 people equally
to one of 500,000. The **population-weighted rate** — defined as
$\sum_c \text{lacking}_c \;/\; \sum_c \text{pop}_c$ — accounts for
this discrepancy and gives the share of the state's *total population*
that lacks plumbing.
:::

## Regression: Population Size as a Predictor

To quantify the relationship between county size and deprivation, we fit
the following linear model:

$$
\operatorname{rate}_i = \alpha + \beta_1 \cdot \log_{10}(\operatorname{pop}_i) + \varepsilon_i, \quad \varepsilon_i \overset{iid}{\sim} \mathcal{N}(0,\,\sigma^2)
$$ {#eq-model}

The log-transformation of population is motivated by the right-skewed
distribution of county sizes and by the expectation that the marginal
effect of population on infrastructure access is decreasing.

```{r}
#| label: fit-model

water_2023_clean <- water_2023_clean |>
  mutate(log_pop = log10(total_pop))

fit <- lm(rate ~ log_pop, data = water_2023_clean)
```

```{r}
#| label: tbl-model
#| echo: false
#| tbl-cap: "OLS coefficient estimates for the model in @eq-model."

tab <- broom::tidy(fit)
tab$p.value <- formatC(tab$p.value, format = "e", digits = 2)
kable(tab, digits = 5,
      col.names = c("Term", "Estimate", "Std. Error",
                    "t-statistic", "p-value"),
      align = c("l", "r", "r", "r", "r"))
```

```{r}
#| label: fig-scatter
#| echo: false
#| fig-cap: "Plumbing deprivation rate vs. log10(county population). The dark blue line is the OLS fit from @eq-model; the shaded band is the 95% confidence interval."
#| fig-height: 5

intercept_val <- round(coef(fit)[], 4)[1]
slope_val     <- round(coef(fit)[], 4)[2]
r2_val        <- round(summary(fit)$r.squared, 3)

ggplot(water_2023_clean, aes(x = log_pop, y = rate)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = rate), alpha = 0.4, size = 1.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x,
              color = "#1a3f6f", fill = "#aec7e8",
              linewidth = 1.2, se = TRUE) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#fdbb84", high = "#b30000",
                       labels = scales::percent_format(),
                       name   = "Deprivation\nrate") +
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks = 3:7,
    labels = c("1,000", "10,000", "100,000", "1M", "10M")
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 0.1)) +
  labs(
    title    = "Larger Counties Have Lower Plumbing Deprivation Rates",
    subtitle = paste0("OLS: rate = ", intercept_val,
                      " + ", slope_val,
                      " x log10(pop)   |   R2 = ", r2_val),
    x = "County population (log scale)",
    y = "Deprivation rate",
    caption = SOURCE_CAPTION
  )
```

The estimated slope $\hat{\beta}_1 =$ `r round(coef(fit)[[2]], 4)` is
negative and highly significant (p < 0.001), confirming that larger
counties tend to have lower plumbing deprivation rates. The model in
@eq-model explains R² = `r round(summary(fit)$r.squared, 3)` of the
variance — a modest but meaningful share, consistent with population
being one of several drivers alongside poverty, geography, and tribal
land status.

## Year-over-Year Change (2022–2023)

```{r}
#| label: change-data

water_change <- water_2022_clean |>
  select(geoid, rate_2022 = rate) |>
  inner_join(
    water_2023_clean |> select(geoid, county, state,
                               rate_2023 = rate, total_pop),
    by = "geoid"
  ) |>
  mutate(
    change    = rate_2023 - rate_2022,
    direction = if_else(change > 0, "Worsened", "Improved")
  )
```

```{r}
#| label: tbl-change-summary
#| tbl-cap: "Summary of county-level change in plumbing deprivation rate between 2022 and 2023."

water_change |>
  summarise(
    `Matched counties`  = n(),
    `Improved`          = sum(direction == "Improved"),
    `Worsened`          = sum(direction == "Worsened"),
    `No change`         = sum(change == 0),
    `Mean delta`        = scales::percent(mean(change),   accuracy = 0.001),
    `Median delta`      = scales::percent(median(change), accuracy = 0.001),
    `Max improvement`   = scales::percent(min(change),    accuracy = 0.01),
    `Max deterioration` = scales::percent(max(change),    accuracy = 0.01)
  ) |>
  kable()
```

```{r}
#| label: fig-change
#| echo: false
#| fig-cap: "Left: 5 most-improved and 5 most-worsened counties (2022–2023). Right: scatter of 2022 vs. 2023 rates — points above the diagonal worsened."
#| fig-height: 5.5

top_changed <- bind_rows(
  water_change |> arrange(change)       |> slice_head(n = 5),
  water_change |> arrange(desc(change)) |> slice_head(n = 5)
)

p_bar <- top_changed |>
  ggplot(aes(x = change, y = fct_reorder(county, change),
             fill = direction)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.72) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "grey50") +
  geom_text(aes(
    label = scales::percent(change, accuracy = 0.01),
    hjust = if_else(change < 0, 1.12, -0.12)
  ), size = 3.2, color = "grey20") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Improved" = "#2166ac",
                               "Worsened" = "#d6604d"),
                    guide = "none") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(),
                     expand = expansion(mult = c(0.22, 0.22))) +
  labs(title = "Largest Changes (2022–2023)",
       x = "Change in rate (pp)", y = NULL) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank())

p_scatter <- water_change |>
  ggplot(aes(x = rate_2022, y = rate_2023)) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0,
              linetype = "dashed", color = "grey50") +
  geom_point(aes(color = change), alpha = 0.45, size = 1.2) +
  ggrepel::geom_label_repel(
    data = top_changed,
    aes(label = county),
    size = 2.5, max.overlaps = 10, box.padding = 0.3
  ) +
  scale_color_gradient2(low = "#2166ac", mid = "grey80",
                        high = "#d6604d", midpoint = 0,
                        labels = scales::percent_format(),
                        name = "delta rate") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 0.1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 0.1)) +
  labs(title = "2022 vs. 2023 Rates",
       x = "Rate 2022", y = "Rate 2023")

p_bar + p_scatter +
  plot_annotation(
    caption = SOURCE_CAPTION,
    theme = theme(plot.caption = element_text(color = "grey55",
                                              size = 8, hjust = 1))
  )
```

As shown in @fig-change, `r sum(water_change$direction == "Improved")`
counties improved and `r sum(water_change$direction == "Worsened")` worsened
between 2022 and 2023. Most counties cluster tightly around the diagonal
(no change), while labelled outliers experienced changes exceeding 5
percentage points in a single year — more plausibly reflecting **survey
sampling variance** in small counties than genuine infrastructure change.

## Geographic Overview

```{r}
#| label: fig-map
#| echo: false
#| fig-cap: "County-level plumbing insecurity across all 50 U.S. states (2023). Each dot is a county; colour = deprivation rate; size = households affected. Alaska and Hawaii are shown as insets via tigris::shift_geometry(). Black rings identify the 10 worst counties."
#| fig-width: 11
#| fig-height: 6.2

# 1. County geometries — all 50 states
counties_sf <- tigris::counties(cb = TRUE, year = 2023,
                                progress_bar = FALSE) |>
  sf::st_transform(crs = 4326)

# 2. State outlines — 50 states only (no territories)
states_sf <- tigris::states(cb = TRUE, year = 2023,
                            progress_bar = FALSE) |>
  filter(!STUSPS %in% c("PR", "VI", "GU", "MP", "AS")) |>
  sf::st_transform(crs = 4326)

# 3. Attach ACS data to county geometries
water_sf <- counties_sf |>
  inner_join(
    water_2023_clean |> select(geoid, rate, plumbing, county, state),
    by = c("GEOID" = "geoid")
  )

# 4. shift_geometry() repositions AK and HI as insets
water_sf_shifted  <- tigris::shift_geometry(water_sf)
states_sf_shifted <- tigris::shift_geometry(states_sf)

# 5. Compute centroids AFTER shift
suppressWarnings({
  centroids_shifted <- water_sf_shifted |>
    sf::st_centroid() |>
    mutate(
      lon = sf::st_coordinates(geometry)[, 1],
      lat = sf::st_coordinates(geometry)[, 2]
    ) |>
    sf::st_drop_geometry() |>
    as_tibble()
})

top10_shifted <- centroids_shifted |> slice_max(order_by = rate, n = 10)

# 6. Plot
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = states_sf_shifted,
          fill = "grey94", color = "white", linewidth = 0.35) +
  geom_point(data = centroids_shifted,
             aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = rate, size = plumbing),
             alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_point(data = top10_shifted,
             aes(x = lon, y = lat),
             shape = 21, color = "black", fill = NA,
             size = 6, stroke = 1.1) +
  ggrepel::geom_label_repel(
    data = top10_shifted,
    aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = county),
    size = 2.4, box.padding = 0.4,
